# Week 1 Full Plan: HTTP, REST, JSON, Status Codes, Request/Response Flow, Postman

## Goal of Week 1
By the end of this week, you should be able to:
- Explain how a frontend request reaches backend and database, then returns to UI.
- Read and write REST APIs with correct HTTP methods and status codes.
- Understand JSON request/response bodies and validation errors.
- Test APIs in Postman with headers, params, body, auth token, and environment variables.

---

## Daily Time Split (2.5 to 3 hours)
- 90 min: Practical API work in your CareFund project
- 45 min: Interview concepts + notes
- 30 min: Postman exercises and debugging
- 15 min: Daily summary log

---

## Day 1 - End-to-End Request/Response Flow

### Theory (45 min)
Learn these concepts:
- Client, server, API, database roles
- Stateless request model
- What happens in one HTTP round-trip
- URL, method, headers, body, response, latency

### Practical (90 min)
Use your project flow: Customer Signup.

Do this mapping:
1. Frontend component/form that triggers signup
2. Angular service method that calls API
3. Backend controller endpoint receiving request
4. Service layer business logic
5. DbContext/model save operation
6. Response sent back (success/error)

Output to write in your notes:
- One simple diagram: Frontend -> API -> Service -> DB -> API -> Frontend
- 10 lines: "How signup works in CareFund"

### Postman (30 min)
- Create collection: CareFund APIs
- Add one request: Signup endpoint
- Send valid payload and capture response

### Day 1 Deliverable
- You can clearly explain one full API flow in your own words.

---

## Day 2 - HTTP Methods + REST Basics

### Theory (45 min)
Understand when to use:
- GET: read data
- POST: create data
- PUT: full update
- PATCH: partial update
- DELETE: remove data

REST naming rules:
- Use nouns in endpoints, not verbs
- Examples: /api/users, /api/donations/{id}

### Practical (90 min)
Review existing backend controllers and classify each endpoint by method.

Create a small table in notes:
- Endpoint
- Method
- Purpose
- Is it RESTful? (Yes/No)

Then improve at least 3 non-REST-style endpoint names in your notes (do not refactor code yet unless needed).

### Postman (30 min)
Send one request for each method:
- GET list
- POST create
- PUT or PATCH update
- DELETE item

### Day 2 Deliverable
- You can choose the correct HTTP method for any CRUD operation.

---

## Day 3 - JSON Deep Understanding

### Theory (45 min)
Learn:
- JSON object, array, number, string, boolean, null
- Nested JSON structures
- Difference between DTO and Entity
- Why backend should not expose internal entities directly

### Practical (90 min)
Pick 3 real request/response models from CareFund:
- Signup request
- Login request/response
- Donation create request

For each model, document:
- Required fields
- Optional fields
- Field types
- Validation constraints

### Postman (30 min)
Test JSON cases:
- Valid body
- Missing required field
- Wrong type (string instead of number)
- Extra unsupported field

Write observed responses and messages.

### Day 3 Deliverable
- You can design valid JSON payloads and identify malformed payloads quickly.

---

## Day 4 - Status Codes + Error Handling

### Theory (45 min)
Master these status codes first:
- 200 OK
- 201 Created
- 204 No Content
- 400 Bad Request
- 401 Unauthorized
- 403 Forbidden
- 404 Not Found
- 409 Conflict
- 422 Unprocessable Entity (if used)
- 500 Internal Server Error

### Practical (90 min)
Take 5 existing endpoints and define:
- Expected success code
- Expected failure codes
- Exact reason for each failure

Then trigger at least 4 errors intentionally (bad payload, unauthorized request, invalid id, duplicate data).

### Postman (30 min)
Create folder: Negative Tests
- Add requests that intentionally fail
- Save each response example with notes

### Day 4 Deliverable
- You can map business scenarios to correct status codes confidently.

---

## Day 5 - Headers, Params, Query, Body, Auth Token

### Theory (45 min)
Learn request parts clearly:
- Path params: /users/{id}
- Query params: /donations?page=1&pageSize=10
- Headers: Content-Type, Authorization
- Body: mainly for POST/PUT/PATCH

JWT basics for now:
- What token contains
- Why Authorization header is needed

### Practical (90 min)
In CareFund, identify endpoints using:
- Route params
- Query params
- Request body
- Auth token

Document examples for each.

### Postman (30 min)
- Use environment variable for baseUrl
- Store JWT token after login
- Reuse token for protected endpoint testing

### Day 5 Deliverable
- You can test authenticated APIs and explain every part of the request.

---

## Day 6 - Postman Professional Workflow

### Theory (30 min)
Understand Postman features:
- Collections
- Environments
- Variables
- Pre-request scripts (basic)
- Tests tab (basic assertions)

### Practical (120 min)
Build one structured collection:
- Auth folder: signup, login, verify
- Charity folder: create, list, status check
- Donation folder: create, list, details
- Admin folder: pending charities, approve/reject

Add at least 5 test assertions, for example:
- status is 200/201
- response has expected field
- token exists after login

### Day 6 Deliverable
- You have a reusable Postman collection that behaves like mini API regression checks.

